lg.l: \before 620-37\ VANESSA is going to own herself in love with CADENUS: and, as an apology for that openness, she pleads thus:

\after 620-37\ Now, pray, my Lord, what is there in all this, which the most virtuous man alive, might not own with his last breath, to be his most sincere, and genuine sentiments? for my own part, I can see nothing in it, but a panegyric upon the purity, and noble nature of virtue!

\before 168-71\ And yet, I have something to censure even in this, besides those passages, which you so justly blame. The lines are these.

\after 168-71\ Give me leave to say, my blood boils with indignation against the folly, the vanity, (I had almost said the blasphemy) of these lines.
Here, my Lord, the finest instinct, and noblest power, with which God hath endowed the human frame, is treated with scandalous contempt, and insolent abuse!

\before 160-63\ The offensive smell with which he poisons them, and every thing about them, is ordinarily the natural effect of great negligence, in the article of cleanliness; and the providential chastisement of it: and yet he charges it upon the nature of the yahoos; forgetting how he had before endowed his favourite VANESSA; when VENUS had sprinkled her with nectar, from her sprig of Amaranthine flowers.
From whence the tender skin assumes,
A sweetness above all perfumes:
From whence, a cleanliness remains,
Incapable of outward stains.
------- that decency of mind,
So lovely in the female kind!
Where no one careless thought intrudes,
Less modest than the speech of prudes.
Where never blush was call'd in aid,
That spurious virtue in a maid:
A virtue but a second hand,
They blush because they understand.
Her soul was suddenly endu'd,
With justice, truth, and fortitude.
With honour, which no breath can stain:
Which malice must attack in vain.
As she advanc'd, that womankind,
Wou'd by her model form their mind:
And all their conduct wou'd be try'd
By her, as an unerring guide.
And tho' she must with grief reflect,
To see a mortal virgin, deck'd
With graces hitherto unknown,
To female breasts, except her own.
How can heavenly wisdom prove,
An instrument to earthly love!
To copy her, few nymphs aspir'd,
Her virtues, fewer swains admir'd.
So stars beyond a certain height,
Give mortals neither heat nor light.
Two maxims she could still produce,
And sad experience taught their use:
That virtue pleas'd by being shown,
Knows nothing, which it dare not own.
Can make us, without fear, disclose
Our inmost secrets to our foes:
That common forms were not design'd,
Directors to a noble mind.
Now, said the nymph, to let you see
My actions with your rules agree,
That I can vulgar forms despise,
And have no secrets to disguise:
I knew by what you said and writ,
How dang'rous things were men of wit;
You caution'd me against their charms,
But never gave me equal arms:
Your lessons found the weakest part,
Aim'd at the head, but reach'd the heart.
